    <span class="eyebrow">Storage guide</span>
    <h1>Steam Deck storage planner: how much space do you actually need?</h1>
    <p class="muted">Baseline/spec-informed guidance for Steam Deck, ROG Ally, Legion Go, and other handheld PCs. I did not run fresh install-size tests for this page; use the linked official sources and the <a href="/calculators/storage-planner/">storage planner calculator</a> before buying storage.</p>

    <div class="callout">Quick answer: 512GB is comfortable for a mixed library, 1TB is the safer long-term handheld target, and a reputable microSD card is still useful for indies, emulation, screenshots, and overflow installs.</div>

    <h2>Start with your real library, not the model name</h2>
    <p>Handheld storage planning gets easier if you group games by install size rather than by hype. A 256GB handheld can feel roomy with lightweight games, but tight if you keep several modern RPGs or open-world games installed at once.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Light library:</strong> indies, roguelikes, retro collections, and cloud-save games you rotate often. 256GB plus a microSD card can work.</li>
      <li><strong>Mixed library:</strong> a few small games, one big RPG, one racing/sports game, and a travel backlog. 512GB is the practical floor.</li>
      <li><strong>Big-game library:</strong> multiple 80GB–150GB installs, mods, shader caches, screenshots, and offline travel. Plan around 1TB internal storage or a 512GB device plus a large microSD card.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why advertised storage is not the same as usable space</h2>
    <p>Every device needs room for the operating system, launchers, updates, shader caches, save data, screenshots, and temporary download files. Leave breathing room instead of filling a drive to the last gigabyte. For a low-friction handheld setup, I like planning with a 15%–20% reserve.</p>

    <h2>Steam Deck: internal SSD vs microSD</h2>
    <p>Valve's official Steam Deck tech specs list microSD expansion, and SteamOS makes moving games between internal storage and a card straightforward. Internal NVMe storage is still the best place for your most-played large games, but microSD remains useful for slower-paced titles, indies, and overflow installs.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Put on internal SSD:</strong> huge open-world games, games that patch often, shader-heavy titles, and anything where load times bother you.</li>
      <li><strong>Put on microSD:</strong> small indies, emulated libraries you legally own, older PC games, visual novels, deckbuilders, and games you keep installed for travel.</li>
      <li><strong>Move before a trip:</strong> if you will be offline, install and launch each game once before leaving so updates and first-run setup do not surprise you.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>ROG Ally and Legion Go planning notes</h2>
    <p>Windows handhelds usually need more storage headroom because launchers, drivers, Windows updates, game bar captures, and temporary files can pile up. If you use Game Pass, Steam, Epic, Battle.net, and mod managers on the same handheld, budget extra space and keep an uninstall rotation.</p>

    <h2>Simple storage formulas</h2>
    <p>Use these as planning shortcuts, then run the calculator for your exact list.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Weekend travel kit:</strong> 1 large game + 5 small games + 20% reserve.</li>
      <li><strong>Daily driver:</strong> 2 large games + 10 small/mid-size games + launchers + 20% reserve.</li>
      <li><strong>Offline backlog:</strong> 3–5 large games + many indies + media/screenshots + 20% reserve.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Buying guidance without affiliate pressure</h2>
    <p>This site may add affiliate links after partner approval, but the storage rule is simple: buy from reputable retailers, check warranty terms, avoid suspiciously cheap high-capacity cards, and prefer reliability over headline speed claims. For microSD cards, look for known gaming-use lines from established brands and keep receipts in case a card fails early.</p>

